Data continuity seems high, with little missingness throughout most vaariables. The variable ‘geol_2nd_class’ is the only variable with significant missingness with 79.4% completeness. I will remove this variable from the dataset and impute means for all other NAs. The feature distribution is varied with many left and right skewed distributions as well as some that are approximately normal and several uniform distributions. All features will need to be scaled and normalized.

Define 3 models (30) — Week 6-1

Define a random forest model using the rand_forest function (engine ranger, mode regression)
Define two other models of your choice. The Week 6-1 zoo (linear_reg, boost_tree, svm_rbf, svm_poly, mlp, bag_mlp, decision_tree) is a good menu — the comparison table in that deck summarizes strengths and weaknesses.
For each model, briefly note (one sentence) why it’s a reasonable candidate for this regression problem — what kind of structure does it capture?


rf_model &lt;- rand_forest() |&gt;
  set_engine("ranger", importance = "impurity") |&gt;
  set_mode("regression")


Random forests are a strong baseline for regression problems, especially when there are non-linear relationships and interactions between predictors. They can capture complex patterns in the data without requiring extensive tuning.


xgb_model &lt;- boost_tree() |&gt;
  set_engine("xgboost", importance = "impurity") |&gt;
  set_mode("regression")


Boosted trees are an ensemble method that build sequential trees to correct the errors of previous trees. They can capture complex relationships and often achieve high predictive performance with tabular data, making them a good candidate for this regression problem.


dt_model &lt;- decision_tree() |&gt;
  set_engine("rpart") |&gt;
  set_mode("regression")


Decision trees provide a simple and interpretable model that can capture non-linear relationships and interactions between predictors.
